08906nam a22011655i 9780691194417DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911944177 a10.1515/97806911944172doi  a(DE-B1597)527299  a(OCoLC)1105199282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQA93 7aMAT0250002bisacsh04a51022304aThe Mathematics of Various Entertaining Subjects :bVolume 3: The Magic of Mathematics /ced. by Jason Rosenhouse, Jennifer Beineke. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b85 color + 71 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPART I. Puzzles and Brainteasers -- t1. Probability in Your Head -- t2. Solving Puzzles Backward -- t3. Spiral Galaxies Font -- t4. Kings, Sages, Hats, and Codes -- t5. How to Predict the Flip of a Coin -- t6. Coins and Logic -- tPART II. Games -- t7. Bingo Paradoxes -- t8. Wiggly Games and Burnside's Lemma -- t9. Losing at Checkers Is Hard -- t10. Chutes and Ladders without Chutes or Ladders -- t11. Bugs, Braids, and Batching -- tPART III. Algebra and Number Theory -- t12. The Magic of Charles Sanders Peirce -- t13. Can You Win Khalou in Five Moves? -- t14. On Partitions into Squares of Distinct Integers Whose Reciprocals Sum to 1 -- t15. Puzzles, Parity Maps, and Plenty of Solutions -- tPART IV. Geometry and Topology -- t16. Should We Call Them Flexa-Bands? -- t17. The Shortest Connection Problem on Triangular Grids -- t18. Entropy of Lego Jumper Plates -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of mathematics is replete with examples of major breakthroughs resulting from the solutions to recreational problems. The modern theory of probability arose out of problems of concern to gamblers, for example, and modern combinatorics grew out of various games and puzzles. Despite this track record and a wealth of popular-level books, research in recreational mathematics has often been neglected. The Mathematics of Various Entertaining Subjects remedies this situation and returns with an all-new third volume, presenting further research into diverse areas of recreational mathematics.This third volume focuses on four areas: puzzles and brainteasers, games, algebra and number theory, and geometry and topology. Among the many topics, readers will create Spiral Galaxies (Japanese symmetric grid puzzles consisting of squares and circles) whose solutions are letters and numbers, delve into a paradox in the game of Bingo, examine the card tricks of mathematician-philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce, and learn about the mathematics behind Legos.Elucidating the many connections between mathematics and games, The Mathematics of Various Entertaining Subjects is sure to challenge and inspire mathematicians and math enthusiasts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematics. 7aMATHEMATICS / Recreations & Games.2bisacsh1 aAlekseyev, Max A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllocca, Michael P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Walker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalof, Barry A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeineke, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenjamin, Arthur T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhargava, Manjul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosboom, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/